1.0 of 5 bubbles
Tourists Beware
Dec 2014 ‚Ä¢ Couples
In December we visited the much anticipated Halong Bay for a 2 night stay aboard the Violet Cruise ship. this trip was fortunately prior arranged through our travel agent in Hanoi. After a 4 hour road trip from Hanoi we arrived at Halong Bay to be advised that the trip may not proceed and that we would not know until 1pm
we boarded with one other couple and had a nice lunch. at 1 we were informed that the trip could proceed but that we may not be able to stay overnight or undertake the planned itinerary. we were take to an island where the options were to climb 400 stairs to the top or sit on the sand. as it was a cold overcast day there was nothing to be gained by climbing to the top. we reboarded and were told that we could overnight on the ship. we had a nice meal and slept well.
the next morning we were told that we could not follow the itinerary as we had to return to port at 9am. we could however choose from 2 tours one being a pearl farm and one to a limestone cave where you had to get down on your hand and knees to traverse. we chose the pearl farm and the other coupe to cave. on return the other couple wanted also to do the pearl farm but this was denied as we had to return to port due to weather.
once we returned to port we were informed that we would be joined by other couples and would not know if the day cruise would proceed until 1pm and then not until 5pm to know if we could overnight again. (as it turned out the cruise went nowhere)
we decided that rather than sit in the harbour until 1pm biding our time we would disembark and get a refund.
this is where the trouble really began as we had paid $1600 for a 2 night stay and were informed that we would get a refund of $300 and have to obtain and pay for our own accommodation onshore.
ultimately our travel agent arranged and paid for the nights accommodation onshore and argued for days with the shipping company about the refund. the Cruise Manager even detailed our short non event itinerary but the shipping company was adamant that it was our decision to leave the ship and our responsibility.
this left a nasty bitter taste in both couples mouths and since that time I have encountered many couples that have had similar experiences in Halong Bay.
as this seems to be a somewhat regular occurance the Violet Cruises should pre-warn tourists that there trip may not proceed and if this does happen what their options are.
we stayed on shore that evening in a Paradise Cruise hotel which was very nice, serviced by good staff and served good food. the whole hotel was full of tourists whose cruises were cancelled and they were all accommodated, fed and offered cruises the next morning.
My advice is not to book with Halong Violet Cruise and be warned that your cruise may be cancelled or changed at any time.
Written January 18, 2015
domtouche
