SpoiledSpouse
Phuket, Thailand20 contributions
3
Overrated & a tourist trap
Nov 2012 ‚Ä¢ Friends
The landscape is impressive but don't expect it to be like the postcards. Maybe this is due to the vast number of tourist boats all going to the same place at the same time and even worse doing the same 'tourist' activity at the same time. There are just under 2000 limestone islets and I think we saw the same 5 from different angles. The boat did not go more than a couple of miles from the coast and you could still see the city for the the entire trip.
We did an overnight cruise with Paradise Cruises and will write a full review under tours but from reading other reviews it sounds like they are all pretty much the same and just follow the same itinerary - parrot fashion.
A few things to consider before booking:
- 3.5 hour journey from Hanoi - private transfers are expensive but really the only way to go.
- Overcrowded with boats and tourists
- Don't travel very far or see that much
- A 'theme park' feel to the whole experience
- Water is dirty with lots of rubbish
A private taylor-made trip may be the way to go if that's possible and I have heard that Bai Tu Long is much better experience so I would suggest a bit of research otherwise in my opinion just buy a postcard, use your imagination and save the money for some other wonder of the world.
Written November 23, 2012
JOP1_10
Sydney, Australia33 contributions
Halong Bay and Halong Violet
Jun 2011 ‚Ä¢ Friends
We visited Halong Bay and stayed on Halong Violet on their so called 2 day 1 night tour. I booked through Vietnam Tours who were very good. Clean, new and comfortable SUV with good driver. I would definitely recommend them.
We stayed on Halong Violet a junk that accommodates only 12 people. I was in the Phoenix suite which was very nice, four poster bed and spa bath, mini bar, wall to ceiling windows.
I would recommend Halong Violet. It wasn't cheap but I believe it is as luxurious as you are probably going to get. The food was very nice and was plentiful. There are plenty of activities if you are so inclined. We visited a fishing village and took a ride on a bamboo boat ( personally I would pass on that excursion and just enjoy the junk whilst everyone else is off it), and visited a cave which the Halong junk people intend to use in the future to host dinners.
Dinner was al a carte and there was a choice of 5 mains, which I found surprising and a reasonable but pricey wine list.
In the morning, Tai chi, a cooking demo (very simple spring rolls - but it was fun)' kayaking and various other activities were offered.
The junk business is highly competitive and there are a lot of junks on the water, some of them pretty large and accommodating large groups. The Halong Cruise people were keen to discuss their future plans and look for future development opportunities as they recognise the competitive environment.
Halong Bay itself had been on my " to visit" list for a number of years. The drive from Hanoi to Halong takes about 3 hours and is dull, there is little to see.
Halong is very obviously being developed as a tourist destination which large, new hotels lining the bay and tour buses everywhere.
The Bay itself is quite pretty but I wasn't overwhelmed by it. It is quite polluted and there is an abundance of junks on it and they all seem to stick together, so it wasn't a secluded relaxing experience.
One night was definitely enough and I don't see myself going back. I have now crossed it off the list.
Written July 2, 2011
