alexandem
Winchcombe, UK21 contributions
1
A-Class Tour to Halong Bay
Apr 2011
My girlfriend and I have just come back from Halong Bay. We had a good experience overall with our trip booked through our hotel with A-Class travel.
That said, before booking its worth considering the following :
- Marketing literature - the literature that A-Class use when promoting the tour is for their flagship boat (the A-Class boat). However, they can't actually guarantee that you'll get that boat (despite any assurances you might receive when booking). Upon arrival in Halong Bay, we were informed that the boat was in the dockyard for repair, and therefore we were transferred to another boat (the Marguerite Junk) which was of a noticably lower standard / quality.
- 1 night or 2 nights ? - we originally booked on the 2 night tour, but there didn't seem to be enough variety in the itinery to warrant the extra time so we ended up changing to the 1 night tour. On balance, I would say 1 night is enough.
- 3 day / 2 night tours - For 2 night tours, it seems to be standard practice to transfer passengers to a different Junk for the second night. We weren't told about this when booking the tour, and other passengers claim that they were given assurances to the contrary. In any case, it seems logical for this to be the norm in order to accomodate the various combinations of tours in the bay. This was a contributing factor in our decision to change to the 1 night tour.
- "Superior" vs "Deluxe" cabin - you'll more than likely be offered an option to "upgrade" your cabin for an extra $20 per person. This didn't seem to be worth it as there wasn't any noticeable difference between the 2 cabin types. Besides, you won't spend any time in your cabin anyway!
- Food - food was distinctly average, although my girlfriend's dietary requirements (no sea-food) were catered for. Make sure you mention this when booking as most of the food served contains some form of sea-food.
- Activities - included kayaking and a visit to the "surprising cave". These were ok, although again, probably not enough to occupy you for 3 days. One criticism I have is that the itinery was very packed and regimented leaving little time to chill out and sunbathe on deck or go swimming. Also, we were told we could go squid fishing on the first night, although this seemed to consist of being handed a net and left to your own devices.
- Drinks - not included in the price (although this is common with nearly all of the Halong Bay cruises). Note that if you bring your own booze on board, you will be expected to pay corkage of $10 per person. The bar on board will expect you to start a tab, so it may be worth keeping a mental note of how many drinks you order to ensure you are charged for the correct amount.
- Tour guide - we had a very good tour guide named "Twan" who spoke perfect English. He definitely helped to make our trip as enjoyable as possible.
- Other passengers - if you're lucky, you'll be a put with a good group of people like we were. We met people of several nationalities with whom we played cards and drank a few beers.
Marguerite Junk
Some observations on the Marguerite Junk
- Shower mouldy and leaked over the bathroom floor
- No WIFI or Computer despite this being promised in the brochure (although, why would you need that anyway!?!?)
So, in a nutshell Halong bay is definitely worth a visit but keep an open mind (to avoid any disappointment!) and be careful not to be taken in by the marketing. 2 days / 1 night is plenty of time to spend there.
nB. It should be noted that after several passengers on our tour complained, the tour operator called all of the hotels to apologise for the disappointment and we were offered partial refunds of the tour price.
